{"title_page": "The Franchise Affair (film)", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=June 2016}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = The Franchise Affair\n| image          = \"The_Franchise_Affair\"_(1951).jpg\n| caption        = UK theatrical poster\n| director       = [[Lawrence Huntington]] \n| producer       = Robert Hall\n| writer         = Robert Hall<br>[[Lawrence Huntington]]\n| based on       = the novel by [[Josephine Tey]]\n| starring       = [[Michael Denison]]<br>[[Dulcie Gray]] \n| cinematography = [[G\u00fcnther Krampf]]\n| music          = [[Philip Green (composer)|Philip Green]]\n| editing         = [[Clifford Boote]]\n| studio = [[Associated British Picture Corporation|ABPC]]\n| distributor   = [[Associated British-Path\u00e9]]\n| released       = 20 February 1951\n| runtime        = 95 minutes\n| country        = [[United Kingdom]]\n| language       = [[English language|English]]\n| gross = \u00a3117,966 (UK)<ref>Vincent Porter, 'The Robert Clark Account', ''Historical Journal of Film, Radio and Television'', Vol 20 No 4, 2000 p493</ref>\n}}\n'''''The Franchise Affair''''' is a 1951 British [[thriller film]] directed by [[Lawrence Huntington]] and starring [[Michael Denison]], [[Dulcie Gray]], [[Anthony Nicholls (actor)|Anthony Nicholls]] and [[Marjorie Fielding]]. It is a faithful adaptation of the novel ''[[The Franchise Affair]]'' by [[Josephine Tey]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bfi.org.uk/films-tv-people/4ce2b6aa9395f |title=BFI &#124; Film & TV Database &#124; The FRANCHISE AFFAIR (1950) |publisher=Ftvdb.bfi.org.uk |date=2009-04-16 |accessdate=2014-03-13}}</ref>\n\n==Plot==\nIn a quiet English town, schoolgirl Betty Kane (Ann Stephens) claims that the owners of an isolated house, spinster Marion Sharpe (Dulcie Gray) and Marion's mother (Marjorie Fielding), kidnapped and beat her. The police believe Betty's story, but local lawyer Robert Blair (Michael Denison), a bachelor, is sceptical. Risking ostracism from the community, Blair quietly sets about proving the innocence of the two women.\n\n==Cast==\n{{Cast listing|\n* [[Michael Denison]] - Robert Blair\n* [[Dulcie Gray]] - Marion Sharpe\n* [[Anthony Nicholls (actor)|Anthony Nicholls]] - Kevin McDermott\n* [[Marjorie Fielding]] - Mrs Sharpe\n* [[Athene Seyler]] - Aunt Lin\n* [[John Bailey (British actor)|John Bailey]] - Detective Inspector Grant\n* [[Ann Stephens]] - Betty Kane\n* [[Hy Hazell]] - Mrs Chadwick\n* [[Kenneth More]] - Stanley Peters\n* [[Avice Landone]] - Mrs Wynn\n* Maureen Glynne - Rose Glynn\n* [[Peter Jones (actor)|Peter Jones]] - Bernard Chadwick\n* [[Moultrie Kelsall]] - Judge\n* [[Martin Boddey]] - Inspector Hallam\n* [[Patrick Troughton]] - Bill Brough\n* Hugh Moxey - Counsel for prosecution\n* [[John Warwick]] - Carley\n* [[Ernest Jay]] - Ramsden\n* [[Everley Gregg]] - Mrs. Jarrett\n* [[Ambrosine Phillpotts]] - Miss Spence\n* [[Jean Anderson]] - Miss Tuff\n* [[Harold Lang (actor)|Harold Lang]] - Bus Inspector\n* John Forrest - Leslis Wynn\n* Lawrence Ray - Albert the waiter\n* [[Victor Maddern]] - Bus Mechanic\n* Doris York - Christina\n* Will Ambro - Heseltine\n}}\n\n==Critical reception==\n*''[[The New York Times]]'' wrote, \"a great many words are spoken and a great deal of tea is consumed in a low-budget British picture, \"The Franchise Affair,\" which made a bedraggled appearance at the Little Carnegie yesterday. And, as may be readily imagined, the sum total of it all is an hour and a half of sheer boredom, unrelieved by any action or surprise.\" <ref>{{cite web|last=Crowther |first=Bosley |url=https://www.nytimes.com/movie/review?res=9B06EEDC113AE53ABC4E53DFB0668389649EDE&action=click&module=Search&region=searchResults%230&version=&url=http%3A%2F%2Fquery.nytimes.com%2Fsearch%2Fsitesearch%2F%3Fvertical%3Dmovies%2F%23%2Fthe%2Bfranchise%2Baffair%2F |title=Movie Review - The Franchise Affair - THE SCREEN |publisher=NYTimes.com |date=1952-06-06 |accessdate=2014-03-13}}</ref>\n*[[Sky Movies]] wrote, \"a neat, well-constructed whodunit - or, rather, was-it-done? - graced by good performances - it was one of several films husband-and-wife team Michael Denison and Dulcie Gray made together - and a leisurely but literate script. Although modest in ambition, the film sustains its drama throughout and there are some fine moments of spicy, English upper-crust wit. Its courtroom scenes also bring a welcome relief from the [[Perry Mason]] style of histrionics. Star-spotters can't miss [[Kenneth More]] in a small role.\" <ref>{{cite web|url=http://skymovies.sky.com/the-franchise-affair/review |title=The Franchise Affair - Sky Movies HD |publisher=Skymovies.sky.com |date=2003-05-21 |accessdate=2014-03-13}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{IMDb title|0042478}}\n\n{{Lawrence Huntington}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Franchise Affair, The (film)}}\n[[Category:1951 films]]\n[[Category:British films]]\n[[Category:1950s thriller films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Lawrence Huntington]]\n\n\n{{1950s-UK-film-stub}}\n{{1950s-thriller-film-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=June 2016}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = The Franchise Affair\n| image          = \"The_Franchise_Affair\"_(1951).jpg\n| caption        = UK theatrical poster\n| director       = [[Lawrence Huntington]] \n| producer       = Robert Hall\n| writer         = Robert Hall<br>[[Lawrence Huntington]]\n| based on       = the novel by [[Josephine Tey]]\n| starring       = [[Michael Denison]]<br>[[Dulcie Gray]] \n| cinematography = [[G\u00fcnther Krampf]]\n| music          = [[Philip Green (composer)|Philip Green]]\n| editing         = [[Clifford Boote]]\n| studio = [[Associated British Picture Corporation|ABPC]]\n| distributor   = [[Associated British-Path\u00e9]]\n| released       = 20 February 1951\n| runtime        = 95 minutes\n| country        = [[United Kingdom]]\n| language       = [[English language|English]]\n| gross = \u00a3117,966 (UK)<ref>Vincent Porter, 'The Robert Clark Account', ''Historical Journal of Film, Radio and Television'', Vol 20 No 4, 2000 p493</ref>\n}}\n'''''The Franchise Affair''''' is a 1951 British [[thriller film]] directed by [[Lawrence Huntington]] and starring [[Michael Denison]], [[Dulcie Gray]], [[Anthony Nicholls (actor)|Anthony Nicholls]] and [[Marjorie Fielding]]. It is a faithful adaptation of the novel ''[[The Franchise Affair]]'' by [[Josephine Tey]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ftvdb.bfi.org.uk/sift/title/33890 |title=BFI &#124; Film & TV Database &#124; The FRANCHISE AFFAIR (1950) |publisher=Ftvdb.bfi.org.uk |date=2009-04-16 |accessdate=2014-03-13}}</ref>\n\n==Plot==\nIn a quiet English town, schoolgirl Betty Kane (Ann Stephens) claims that the owners of an isolated house, spinster Marion Sharpe (Dulcie Gray) and Marion's mother (Marjorie Fielding), kidnapped and beat her. The police believe Betty's story, but local lawyer Robert Blair (Michael Denison), a bachelor, is sceptical. Risking ostracism from the community, Blair quietly sets about proving the innocence of the two women.\n\n==Cast==\n{{Cast listing|\n* [[Michael Denison]] - Robert Blair\n* [[Dulcie Gray]] - Marion Sharpe\n* [[Anthony Nicholls (actor)|Anthony Nicholls]] - Kevin McDermott\n* [[Marjorie Fielding]] - Mrs Sharpe\n* [[Athene Seyler]] - Aunt Lin\n* [[John Bailey (British actor)|John Bailey]] - Detective Inspector Grant\n* [[Ann Stephens]] - Betty Kane\n* [[Hy Hazell]] - Mrs Chadwick\n* [[Kenneth More]] - Stanley Peters\n* [[Avice Landone]] - Mrs Wynn\n* Maureen Glynne - Rose Glynn\n* [[Peter Jones (actor)|Peter Jones]] - Bernard Chadwick\n* [[Moultrie Kelsall]] - Judge\n* [[Martin Boddey]] - Inspector Hallam\n* [[Patrick Troughton]] - Bill Brough\n* Hugh Moxey - Counsel for prosecution\n* [[John Warwick]] - Carley\n* [[Ernest Jay]] - Ramsden\n* [[Everley Gregg]] - Mrs. Jarrett\n* [[Ambrosine Phillpotts]] - Miss Spence\n* [[Jean Anderson]] - Miss Tuff\n* [[Harold Lang (actor)|Harold Lang]] - Bus Inspector\n* John Forrest - Leslis Wynn\n* Lawrence Ray - Albert the waiter\n* [[Victor Maddern]] - Bus Mechanic\n* Doris York - Christina\n* Will Ambro - Heseltine\n}}\n\n==Critical reception==\n*''[[The New York Times]]'' wrote, \"a great many words are spoken and a great deal of tea is consumed in a low-budget British picture, \"The Franchise Affair,\" which made a bedraggled appearance at the Little Carnegie yesterday. And, as may be readily imagined, the sum total of it all is an hour and a half of sheer boredom, unrelieved by any action or surprise.\" <ref>{{cite web|last=Crowther |first=Bosley |url=https://www.nytimes.com/movie/review?res=9B06EEDC113AE53ABC4E53DFB0668389649EDE&action=click&module=Search&region=searchResults%230&version=&url=http%3A%2F%2Fquery.nytimes.com%2Fsearch%2Fsitesearch%2F%3Fvertical%3Dmovies%2F%23%2Fthe%2Bfranchise%2Baffair%2F |title=Movie Review - The Franchise Affair - THE SCREEN |publisher=NYTimes.com |date=1952-06-06 |accessdate=2014-03-13}}</ref>\n*[[Sky Movies]] wrote, \"a neat, well-constructed whodunit - or, rather, was-it-done? - graced by good performances - it was one of several films husband-and-wife team Michael Denison and Dulcie Gray made together - and a leisurely but literate script. Although modest in ambition, the film sustains its drama throughout and there are some fine moments of spicy, English upper-crust wit. Its courtroom scenes also bring a welcome relief from the [[Perry Mason]] style of histrionics. Star-spotters can't miss [[Kenneth More]] in a small role.\" <ref>{{cite web|url=http://skymovies.sky.com/the-franchise-affair/review |title=The Franchise Affair - Sky Movies HD |publisher=Skymovies.sky.com |date=2003-05-21 |accessdate=2014-03-13}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{IMDb title|0042478}}\n\n{{Lawrence Huntington}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Franchise Affair, The (film)}}\n[[Category:1951 films]]\n[[Category:British films]]\n[[Category:19